        <!-- Project Overview -->
        <div class="project-section">
            <h3>Project Overview</h3>
            <p>
                This project demonstrates how to package and deploy a simple <strong>Node.js application</strong> using <strong>Docker containers</strong> and automate the build process using <strong>CircleCI</strong>.
            </p>
            <ul>
                <li>Containerized a Node.js application using a Dockerfile.</li>
                <li>Built and ran Docker images locally to verify functionality.</li>
                <li>Pushed the Docker image to <strong>Docker Hub</strong> for cloud storage.</li>
                <li>Configured <strong>CircleCI</strong> to automatically build and publish Docker images upon every GitHub commit.</li>
            </ul>
            <p>The goal was to understand the fundamentals of containerization and CI/CD automation using Docker and CircleCI.</p>
        </div>

        <!-- Architecture -->
        <div class="project-section alt-bg">
            <h3>Architecture Explanation</h3>
            <p>The architecture includes the following components:</p>
            <ul>
                <li><strong>Developer Machine</strong> – Builds Docker images from the Node.js source code using a Dockerfile.</li>
                <li><strong>GitHub Repository</strong> – Stores source code and triggers CircleCI pipeline on each commit.</li>
                <li><strong>CircleCI</strong> – Builds the Docker image in the cloud and pushes it to Docker Hub automatically.</li>
                <li><strong>Docker Hub</strong> – Acts as a container registry for storing and sharing Docker images.</li>
                <li><strong>Local or Cloud Environment (e.g., EC2)</strong> – Pulls and runs the container image to launch the application.</li>
            </ul>
        </div>

        <!-- Key Learnings -->
        <div class="project-section">
            <h3>Key Learnings</h3>
            <ul>
                <li>Understood how Docker containers isolate applications and dependencies.</li>
                <li>Created and tested a Dockerfile to containerize a Node.js application.</li>
                <li>Published Docker images to Docker Hub for global accessibility.</li>
                <li>Configured CircleCI for automated builds and deployments (CI/CD).</li>
                <li>Learned how CI/CD reduces manual deployment efforts and ensures consistent builds.</li>
            </ul>
        </div>

        <!-- Best Practices -->
        <div class="project-section alt-bg">
            <h3>Notes & Best Practices</h3>
            <p>
                In this lab project, a single container was used to host the Node.js application. In real-world production systems:
            </p>
            <ul>
                <li>Applications are often split into multiple containers (frontend, backend, database) for modularity.</li>
                <li>Container images are deployed and orchestrated using services like <strong>Amazon ECS</strong> or <strong>Kubernetes</strong>.</li>
                <li>Images are stored in secure registries like <strong>Amazon ECR</strong> instead of public Docker Hub.</li>
                <li>Environment variables and secrets are managed through CI/CD pipelines or AWS Secrets Manager.</li>
                <li>Proper tagging and versioning of Docker images help maintain deployment traceability.</li>
            </ul>
        </div>

